[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] In computer science, **amortized analysis** is a method for analyzing a given algorithm's complexity, or how much of a resource, especially time or memory, it takes to execute.
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] The motivation for amortized analysis is that looking at the worst-case run time can be too pessimistic.
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] Instead, amortized analysis averages the running times of operations in a sequence over that sequence.
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] For a given operation of an algorithm, certain situations (e.g., input parametrizations or data structure contents) may imply a significant cost in resources, whereas other situations may not be as costly.
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] The amortized analysis considers both the costly and less costly operations together over the whole sequence of operations.
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] This may include accounting for different types of input, length of the input, and other factors that affect its performance.
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] Amortized analysis initially emerged from a method called aggregate analysis, which is now subsumed by amortized analysis.
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] The technique was first formally introduced by Robert Tarjan in his 1985 paper *Amortized Computational Complexity*, which addressed the need for a more useful form of analysis than the common probabilistic methods used.
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] Amortization was initially used for very specific types of algorithms, particularly those involving binary trees and union operations.
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] However, it is now ubiquitous and comes into play when analyzing many other algorithms as well.
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] Amortized analysis requires knowledge of which series of operations are possible.
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] This is most commonly the case with data structures, which have a state that persists between operations.
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] The basic idea is that a worst-case operation can alter the state in such a way that the worst case cannot occur again for a long time, thus "amortizing" its cost.
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] There are generally three methods for performing amortized analysis: the aggregate method, the accounting method, and the potential method.
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] All of these give correct answers; the choice of which to use depends on which is most convenient for a particular situation.
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] Consider a dynamic array that grows in size as more elements are added to it, such as `ArrayList` in Java or `std::vector` in C++.
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] If we started out with a dynamic array of size 4, we could push 4 elements onto it, and each operation would take constant time.
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] Yet pushing a fifth element onto that array would take longer as the array would have to create a new array of a scaled size, copy the old elements onto the new array, then add the new element.
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] The next few push operations would similarly take constant time, then the subsequent addition would require another slow scaling of the array size.
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] In general, for an arbitrary number n of pushes to an array of any initial size, the times for steps that scale the array add in a geometric series to $O(n)$ , while the constant times for each remaining push also add to $O(n)$ .
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] Therefore the average time per push operation is $O(n)/n=O(1)$ .
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] This reasoning can be formalized and generalized to more complicated data structures using amortized analysis.
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] The enqueue operation just pushes an element onto the input array; this operation does not depend on the lengths of either input or output and therefore runs in constant time.
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] However the dequeue operation is more complicated.
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] If the output array already has some elements in it, then dequeue runs in constant time; otherwise, dequeue takes ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ time to add all the elements onto the output array from the input array, where *n* is the current length of the input array.
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] After copying *n* elements from input, we can perform *n* dequeue operations, each taking constant time, before the output array is empty again.
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] Thus, we can perform a sequence of *n* dequeue operations in only ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ time, which implies that the amortized time of each dequeue operation is ⁠ $O(1)$ ⁠.
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] Alternatively, we can charge the cost of copying any item from the input array to the output array to the earlier enqueue operation for that item.
[src:complexity-theory/amortized-analysis] This charging scheme doubles the amortized time for enqueue but reduces the amortized time for dequeue to ⁠ $O(1)$ ⁠.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] In computer science and operations research, **approximation algorithms** are efficient algorithms that find approximate solutions to optimization problems (in particular NP-hard problems) with provable guarantees on the distance of the returned solution to the optimal one.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] Approximation algorithms naturally arise in the field of theoretical computer science as a consequence of the widely believed P ≠ NP conjecture.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] Under this conjecture, a wide class of optimization problems cannot be solved exactly in polynomial time.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] The field of approximation algorithms, therefore, tries to understand how closely it is possible to approximate optimal solutions to such problems in polynomial time.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] In an overwhelming majority of the cases, the guarantee of such algorithms is a multiplicative one expressed as an approximation ratio or approximation factor i.e., the optimal solution is always guaranteed to be within a (predetermined) multiplicative factor of the returned solution.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] However, there are also many approximation algorithms that provide an additive guarantee on the quality of the returned solution.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] An example of an approximation algorithm with a multiplicative guarantee is the Christofides-Serdyukov algorithm for the Travelling salesman problem.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] It provides a travelling salesman tour in a metric of length at most 3/2 times that of a shortest such tour.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] A classic example of approximation algorithm providing an additive guarantee is the constructive proof of Vizing’s theorem.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] It shows how to color the edges of an undirected graph with at most $\Delta +1$ colors, where $\Delta$ is the maximum degree of any node.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] Since every edge incident on a maximum-degree node must have a different color, the constructive proof of the theorem gives a polynomial-time algorithm that uses at most one additional color than the minimum needed.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] A notable example of an approximation algorithm that provides *both* is the classic approximation algorithm of Lenstra, Shmoys and Tardos for scheduling on unrelated parallel machines.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] The design and analysis of approximation algorithms crucially involves a mathematical proof certifying the quality of the returned solutions in the worst case.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] This distinguishes them from heuristics such as annealing or genetic algorithms, which find reasonably good solutions on some inputs, but provide no clear indication at the outset on when they may succeed or fail.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] There is widespread interest in theoretical computer science to better understand the limits to which we can approximate certain famous optimization problems.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] For example, one of the long-standing open questions in computer science is to determine whether there is an algorithm that outperforms the 2-approximation for the Steiner Forest problem by Agrawal et al.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] The desire to understand hard optimization problems from the perspective of approximability is motivated by the discovery of surprising mathematical connections and broadly applicable techniques to design algorithms for hard optimization problems.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] One well-known example of the former is the Goemans–Williamson algorithm for maximum cut, which solves a graph theoretic problem using a semidefinite program coming from the first level of the sum of squares hierarchy.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] A simple example of an approximation algorithm is one for the minimum vertex cover problem, where the goal is to choose the smallest set of vertices such that every edge in the input graph contains at least one chosen vertex.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] One way to find a vertex cover is to repeat the following process: find an uncovered edge, add both its endpoints to the cover, and remove all edges incident to either vertex from the graph.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] As any vertex cover of the input graph must use a distinct vertex to cover each edge that was considered in the process (since it forms a matching), the vertex cover produced, therefore, is at most twice as large as the optimal one.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] In other words, this is a constant-factor approximation algorithm with an approximation factor of 2.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] Under the recent unique games conjecture, this factor is even the best possible one.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] Others are impossible to approximate within any constant, or even polynomial, factor unless P = NP, as in the case of the maximum clique problem.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] Therefore, an important benefit of studying approximation algorithms is a fine-grained classification of the difficulty of various NP-hard problems beyond the one afforded by the theory of NP-completeness.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] In other words, although NP-complete problems may be equivalent (under polynomial-time reductions) to each other from the perspective of exact solutions, the corresponding optimization problems behave very differently from the perspective of approximate solutions.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] By now there are several established techniques to design approximation algorithms.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] This involves modeling the considered problem with an appropriate mathematical programming formulation (typically a convex programming) such as Linear programming, Semidefinite programming, etc, to obtain a relaxation of solutions for the problem.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] Then further algorithmic techniques for these formulations are applied.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] Embedding the problem in some metric and then solving the problem on the metric.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] Random sampling and the use of randomness in general in conjunction with the methods above.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] While approximation algorithms always provide an a priori worst case guarantee (be it additive or multiplicative), in some cases they also provide an a posteriori guarantee that is often much better.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] This is often the case for algorithms that work by solving a convex relaxation of the optimization problem on the given input.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] For example, there is a different approximation algorithm for minimum vertex cover that solves a linear programming relaxation to find a vertex cover that is at most twice the value of the relaxation.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] Since the value of the relaxation is never larger than the size of the optimal vertex cover, this yields another 2-approximation algorithm.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] While this is similar to the a priori guarantee of the previous approximation algorithm, the guarantee of the latter can be much better (indeed when the value of the LP relaxation is far from the size of the optimal vertex cover).
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] Approximation algorithms as a research area is closely related to and informed by inapproximability theory where the non-existence of efficient algorithms with certain approximation ratios is proved (conditioned on widely believed hypotheses such as the P ≠ NP conjecture) by means of reductions.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] In the case of the metric traveling salesman problem, the best known inapproximability result rules out algorithms with an approximation ratio less than 123/122 ≈ 1.008196 unless P = NP, Karpinski, Lampis, Schmied.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] Coupled with the knowledge of the existence of Christofides' 1.5 approximation algorithm, this tells us that the threshold of approximability for metric traveling salesman (if it exists) is somewhere between 123/122 and 1.5.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] While inapproximability results have been proved since the 1970s, such results were obtained by ad hoc means and no systematic understanding was available at the time.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] It is only since the 1990 result of Feige, Goldwasser, Lovász, Safra and Szegedy on the inapproximability of Independent Set and the famous PCP theorem, that modern tools for proving inapproximability results were uncovered.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] The PCP theorem, for example, shows that Johnson's 1974 approximation algorithms for Max SAT, set cover, independent set and coloring all achieve the optimal approximation ratio, assuming P ≠ NP.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] Not all approximation algorithms are suitable for direct practical applications.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] Implementation and running time issues aside, the guarantees provided by approximation algorithms may themselves not be strong enough to justify their consideration in practice.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] Despite their inability to be used "out of the box" in practical applications, the ideas and insights behind the design of such algorithms can often be incorporated in other ways in practical algorithms.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] In this way, the study of even very expensive algorithms is not a completely theoretical pursuit as they can yield valuable insights.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] In other cases, even if the initial results are of purely theoretical interest, over time, with an improved understanding, the algorithms may be refined to become more practical.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] One such example is the initial PTAS for Euclidean TSP by Sanjeev Arora (and independently by Joseph Mitchell) which had a prohibitive running time of $n^{O(1/\epsilon )}$ for a $1+\epsilon$ approximation.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] Yet, within a year these ideas were incorporated into a near-linear time $O(n\log n)$ algorithm for any constant $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] Given a feasible solution $s\in S(i)$ , with $s\neq s^{*}$ , we would want a guarantee of the quality of the solution, which is a performance to be guaranteed (approximation factor).
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] The approximation can be proven *tight* (*tight approximation*) by demonstrating that there exist instances where the algorithm performs at the approximation limit, indicating the tightness of the bound.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] In this case, it's enough to construct an input instance designed to force the algorithm into a worst-case scenario.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] For some approximation algorithms it is possible to prove certain properties about the approximation of the optimum result.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] The factor *ρ* is called the *relative performance guarantee*.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] where *f*(*y*) is the value/cost of the solution *y* for the instance *x*.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] Clearly, the performance guarantee is greater than or equal to 1 and equal to 1 if and only if *y* is an optimal solution.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] If an algorithm *A* guarantees to return solutions with a performance guarantee of at most *r*(*n*), then *A* is said to be an *r*(*n*)-approximation algorithm and has an *approximation ratio* of *r*(*n*).
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] Likewise, a problem with an *r*(*n*)-approximation algorithm is said to be r*(*n*)*-*approximable* or have an approximation ratio of *r*(*n*).
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] For minimization problems, the two different guarantees provide the same result and that for maximization problems, a relative performance guarantee of ρ is equivalent to a performance guarantee of $r=\rho ^{-1}$ .
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] In the literature, both definitions are common but it is clear which definition is used since, for maximization problems, as ρ ≤ 1 while r ≥ 1.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] That is to say that $\mathrm {P} _{A}$ is the largest bound on the approximation ratio, *r*, that one sees over all possible instances of the problem.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] That is to say that it is the same as the *absolute performance ratio*, with a lower bound *n* on the size of problem instances.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] These two types of ratios are used because there exist algorithms where the difference between these two is significant.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] In the literature, an approximation ratio for a maximization (minimization) problem of *c* - ϵ (min: *c* + ϵ) means that the algorithm has an approximation ratio of *c* ∓ ϵ for arbitrary ϵ > 0 but that the ratio has not (or cannot) be shown for ϵ = 0.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] An example of this is the optimal inapproximability — inexistence of approximation — ratio of 7 / 8 + ϵ for satisfiable MAX-3SAT instances due to Johan Håstad.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] As mentioned previously, when *c* = 1, the problem is said to have a polynomial-time approximation scheme.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] An ϵ-term may appear when an approximation algorithm introduces a multiplicative error and a constant error while the minimum optimum of instances of size *n* goes to infinity as *n* does.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] In this case, the approximation ratio is *c* ∓ *k* / OPT = *c* ∓ o(1) for some constants *c* and *k*.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] Given arbitrary ϵ > 0, one can choose a large enough *N* such that the term *k* / OPT < ϵ for every *n ≥ N*.
[src:complexity-theory/approximation-algorithm] For every fixed ϵ, instances of size *n < N* can be solved by brute force, thereby showing an approximation ratio — existence of approximation algorithms with a guarantee — of *c* ∓ ϵ for every ϵ > 0.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] In theoretical computer science and mathematics, **computational complexity theory** focuses on classifying computational problems according to their resource usage, and explores the relationships between these classifications.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] A computational problem is a task solved by a computer and is solvable by mechanical application of mathematical steps, such as an algorithm.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] A problem is regarded as inherently difficult if its solution requires significant resources, whatever the algorithm used.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The theory formalizes this intuition, by introducing mathematical models of computation to study these problems and quantifying their computational complexity, i.e., the amount of resources needed to solve them, such as time and storage.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Other measures of complexity are also used, such as the amount of communication (used in communication complexity), the number of gates in a circuit (used in circuit complexity) and the number of processors (used in parallel computing).
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] One of the roles of computational complexity theory is to determine the practical limits on what computers can and cannot do.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The P versus NP problem, one of the seven Millennium Prize Problems, is part of the field of computational complexity.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Closely related fields in theoretical computer science are analysis of algorithms and computability theory.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] More precisely, computational complexity theory tries to classify problems that can or cannot be solved with appropriately restricted resources.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] In turn, imposing restrictions on the available resources is what distinguishes computational complexity from computability theory: the latter theory asks what kinds of problems can, in principle, be solved algorithmically.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] A computational problem can be viewed as an infinite collection of *instances* together with a set (possibly empty) of *solutions* for every instance.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The input string for a computational problem is referred to as a problem instance, and should not be confused with the problem itself.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] In computational complexity theory, a problem refers to the abstract question to be solved.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] In contrast, an instance of this problem is a rather concrete utterance, which can serve as the input for a decision problem.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] For example, consider the problem of primality testing.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The instance is a number (e.g., 15) and the solution is "yes" if the number is prime and "no" otherwise (in this case, 15 is not prime and the answer is "no").
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Stated another way, the *instance* is a particular input to the problem, and the *solution* is the output corresponding to the given input.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] To further highlight the difference between a problem and an instance, consider the following instance of the decision version of the travelling salesman problem: Is there a route of at most 2000 kilometres passing through all of Germany's 14 largest cities?
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The quantitative answer to this particular problem instance is of little use for solving other instances of the problem, such as asking for a round trip through 14 sites in Milan whose total length is at most 10 km.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] For this reason, complexity theory addresses computational problems and not particular problem instances.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] When considering computational problems, a problem instance is a string over an alphabet.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Usually, the alphabet is taken to be the binary alphabet (i.e., the set {0,1}), and thus the strings are bitstrings.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] As in a real-world computer, mathematical objects other than bitstrings must be suitably encoded.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] For example, integers can be represented in binary notation, and graphs can be encoded directly via their adjacency matrices, or by encoding their adjacency lists in binary.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Even though some proofs of complexity-theoretic theorems regularly assume some concrete choice of input encoding, one tries to keep the discussion abstract enough to be independent of the precise choice of encoding.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] This can be achieved by ensuring that different representations can be transformed into each other efficiently.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Decision problems are one of the central objects of study in computational complexity theory.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] A decision problem is a type of computational problem where the answer is either *yes* or *no* (alternatively, 1 or 0).
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] A decision problem can be viewed as a formal language, where the members of the language are instances whose output is yes, and the non-members are those instances whose output is no.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The objective is to decide, with the aid of an algorithm, whether a given input string is a member of the formal language under consideration.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] If the algorithm deciding this problem returns the answer *yes*, the algorithm is said to accept the input string, otherwise it is said to reject the input.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] An example of a decision problem is the following.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The problem consists in deciding whether the given graph is connected or not.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The formal language associated with this decision problem is then the set of all connected graphs—to obtain a precise definition of this language, one has to decide how graphs are encoded as binary strings.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] A function problem is a computational problem where a single output (of a total function) is expected for every input, but the output can be more complex than that of a decision problem—that is, the output is not just yes or no.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Notable examples include the traveling salesman problem and the integer factorization problem.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] It is tempting to think that the notion of function problems is much richer than the notion of decision problems.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] However, this is not really the case, since function problems can be recast as decision problems.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] For example, the multiplication of two integers can be expressed as the set of triples $(a,b,c)$ such that the relation $a\times b=c$ holds.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Deciding whether a given triple is a member of this set corresponds to solving the problem of multiplying two numbers.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] To measure the difficulty of solving a computational problem, one may wish to see how much time the best algorithm requires to solve the problem.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] However, the running time may, in general, depend on the instance.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] In particular, larger instances will require more time to solve.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Thus the time required to solve a problem (or the space required, or any measure of complexity) is calculated as a function of the size of the instance.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The input size is typically measured in bits.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Complexity theory studies how algorithms scale as input size increases.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] For instance, in the problem of finding whether a graph is connected, how much more time does it take to solve a problem for a graph with $2n$ vertices compared to the time taken for a graph with n vertices?
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] If the input size is n , the time taken can be expressed as a function of n .
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Since the time taken on different inputs of the same size can be different, the worst-case time complexity $T(n)$ is defined to be the maximum time taken over all inputs of size n .
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] If $T(n)$ is a polynomial in n , then the algorithm is said to be a polynomial time algorithm.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Cobham's thesis argues that a problem can be solved with a feasible amount of resources if and only if it admits a polynomial-time algorithm.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] A Turing machine is a mathematical model of a general computing machine.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] It is a theoretical device that manipulates symbols contained on a strip of tape.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Turing machines are not intended as a practical computing technology, but rather as a general model of a computing machine—anything from an advanced supercomputer to a mathematician with a pencil and paper.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] It is believed that if a problem can be solved by an algorithm, there exists a Turing machine that solves the problem.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Indeed, this is the statement of the Church–Turing thesis.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Furthermore, it is known that everything that can be computed on other models of computation known to us today, such as a RAM machine, Conway's Game of Life, cellular automata, lambda calculus or any programming language can be computed on a Turing machine.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Since Turing machines are easy to analyze mathematically, and are believed to be as powerful as any other model of computation, the Turing machine is the most commonly used model in complexity theory.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Many types of Turing machines are used to define complexity classes, such as deterministic Turing machines, probabilistic Turing machines, non-deterministic Turing machines, quantum Turing machines, symmetric Turing machines and alternating Turing machines.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] They are all equally powerful in principle, but when resources (such as time or space) are bounded, some of these may be more powerful than others.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] A deterministic Turing machine is the most basic Turing machine, which uses a fixed set of rules to determine its future actions.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] A probabilistic Turing machine is a deterministic Turing machine with an extra supply of random bits.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The ability to make probabilistic decisions often helps algorithms solve problems more efficiently.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Algorithms that use random bits are called randomized algorithms.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] A non-deterministic Turing machine is a deterministic Turing machine with an added feature of non-determinism, which allows a Turing machine to have multiple possible future actions from a given state.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] One way to view non-determinism is that the Turing machine branches into many possible computational paths at each step, and if it solves the problem in any of these branches, it is said to have solved the problem.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Clearly, this model is not meant to be a physically realizable model, it is just a theoretically interesting abstract machine that gives rise to particularly interesting complexity classes.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] For examples, see non-deterministic algorithm.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Many machine models different from the standard multi-tape Turing machines have been proposed in the literature, for example random-access machines.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Perhaps surprisingly, each of these models can be converted to another without providing any extra computational power.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The time and memory consumption of these alternate models may vary.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] What all these models have in common is that the machines operate deterministically.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] However, some computational problems are easier to analyze in terms of more unusual resources.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] For example, a non-deterministic Turing machine is a computational model that is allowed to branch out to check many different possibilities at once.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The non-deterministic Turing machine has very little to do with how we physically want to compute algorithms, but its branching exactly captures many of the mathematical models we want to analyze, so that non-deterministic time is a very important resource in analyzing computational problems.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] For a precise definition of what it means to solve a problem using a given amount of time and space, a computational model such as the deterministic Turing machine is used.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The time required by a deterministic Turing machine M on input x is the total number of state transitions, or steps, the machine makes before it halts and outputs the answer ("yes" or "no").
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] A Turing machine M is said to operate within time $f(n)$ if the time required by M on each input of length n is at most $f(n)$ .
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] A decision problem A can be solved in time $f(n)$ if there exists a Turing machine operating in time $f(n)$ that solves the problem.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Since complexity theory is interested in classifying problems based on their difficulty, one defines sets of problems based on some criteria.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] For instance, the set of problems solvable within time $f(n)$ on a deterministic Turing machine is then denoted by DTIME( $f(n)$ ).
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Analogous definitions can be made for space requirements.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Although time and space are the most well-known complexity resources, any complexity measure can be viewed as a computational resource.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Complexity measures are very generally defined by the Blum complexity axioms.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Other complexity measures used in complexity theory include communication complexity, circuit complexity, and decision tree complexity.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The complexity of an algorithm is often expressed using big *O* notation.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The best, worst and average case complexity refer to three different ways of measuring the time complexity (or any other complexity measure) of different inputs of the same size.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Average-case complexity: This is the complexity of solving the problem on average, for inputs of size *n*.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] This complexity is only defined with respect to a probability distribution over the inputs.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] For instance, if all inputs of the same size are assumed to be equally likely to appear, the average case complexity can be defined with respect to the uniform distribution over all inputs of size n .
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Amortized analysis: Amortized analysis considers both the costly and less costly operations together over the whole series of operations of the algorithm.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Worst-case complexity: This is the complexity of solving the problem for the worst input of size n .
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The order from cheap to costly is: Best, average (of discrete uniform distribution), amortized, worst.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] For example, the deterministic sorting algorithm quicksort addresses the problem of sorting a list of integers.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The worst-case is when the pivot is always the largest or smallest value in the list (so the list is never divided).
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] In this case, the algorithm takes time *O*( $n^{2}$ ).
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] If we assume that all possible permutations of the input list are equally likely, the average time taken for sorting is $O(n\log n)$ .
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The best case occurs when each pivoting divides the list in half, also needing $O(n\log n)$ time.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] To classify the computation time (or similar resources, such as space consumption), it is helpful to demonstrate upper and lower bounds on the maximum amount of time required by the most efficient algorithm to solve a given problem.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The complexity of an algorithm is usually taken to be its worst-case complexity unless specified otherwise.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Analyzing a particular algorithm falls under the field of analysis of algorithms.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] To show an upper bound $T(n)$ on the time complexity of a problem, one needs to show only that there is a particular algorithm with running time at most $T(n)$ .
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] However, proving lower bounds is much more difficult, since lower bounds make a statement about all possible algorithms that solve a given problem.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The phrase "all possible algorithms" includes not just the algorithms known today, but any algorithm that might be discovered in the future.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] To show a lower bound of $T(n)$ for a problem requires showing that no algorithm can have time complexity lower than $T(n)$ .
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Upper and lower bounds are usually stated using the big *O* notation, which hides constant factors and smaller terms.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] This makes the bounds independent of the specific details of the computational model used.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] A **complexity class** is a set of problems of related complexity.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Some complexity classes have complicated definitions that do not fit into this framework.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] But bounding the computation time above by some concrete function $f(n)$ often yields complexity classes that depend on the chosen machine model.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] For instance, the language $\{xx\mid x{\text{ is any binary string}}\}$ can be solved in linear time on a multi-tape Turing machine, but necessarily requires quadratic time in the model of single-tape Turing machines.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] If we allow polynomial variations in running time, Cobham-Edmonds thesis states that "the time complexities in any two reasonable and general models of computation are polynomially related" (Goldreich 2008, Chapter 1.2).
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] This forms the basis for the complexity class P, which is the set of decision problems solvable by a deterministic Turing machine within polynomial time.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The corresponding set of function problems is FP.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Many important complexity classes can be defined by bounding the time or space used by the algorithm.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Logarithmic-space classes do not account for the space required to represent the problem.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] It turns out that PSPACE = NPSPACE and EXPSPACE = NEXPSPACE by Savitch's theorem.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Classes like IP and AM are defined using Interactive proof systems.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] ALL is the class of all decision problems.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] For the complexity classes defined in this way, it is desirable to prove that relaxing the requirements on (say) computation time indeed defines a bigger set of problems.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] In particular, although DTIME( n ) is contained in DTIME( $n^{2}$ ), it would be interesting to know if the inclusion is strict.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] For time and space requirements, the answer to such questions is given by the time and space hierarchy theorems respectively.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] They are called hierarchy theorems because they induce a proper hierarchy on the classes defined by constraining the respective resources.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Thus there are pairs of complexity classes such that one is properly included in the other.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Having deduced such proper set inclusions, we can proceed to make quantitative statements about how much more additional time or space is needed in order to increase the number of problems that can be solved.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] More precisely, the time hierarchy theorem states that ${\mathsf {DTIME}}{\big (}o(f(n)){\big )}\subsetneq {\mathsf {DTIME}}{\big (}f(n)\cdot \log(f(n)){\big )}$ .
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The space hierarchy theorem states that ${\mathsf {DSPACE}}{\big (}o(f(n)){\big )}\subsetneq {\mathsf {DSPACE}}{\big (}f(n){\big )}$ .
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The time and space hierarchy theorems form the basis for most separation results of complexity classes.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] For instance, the time hierarchy theorem tells us that P is strictly contained in EXPTIME, and the space hierarchy theorem tells us that L is strictly contained in PSPACE.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Many complexity classes are defined using the concept of a reduction.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] A reduction is a transformation of one problem into another problem.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] It captures the informal notion of a problem being at most as difficult as another problem.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] For instance, if a problem X can be solved using an algorithm for Y , X is no more difficult than Y , and we say that X *reduces* to Y .
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] There are many different types of reductions, based on the method of reduction, such as Cook reductions, Karp reductions and Levin reductions, and the bound on the complexity of reductions, such as polynomial-time reductions or log-space reductions.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The most commonly used reduction is a polynomial-time reduction.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] This means that the reduction process takes polynomial time.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] For example, the problem of squaring an integer can be reduced to the problem of multiplying two integers.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] This means an algorithm for multiplying two integers can be used to square an integer.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Indeed, this can be done by giving the same input to both inputs of the multiplication algorithm.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Thus we see that squaring is not more difficult than multiplication, since squaring can be reduced to multiplication.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] This motivates the concept of a problem being hard for a complexity class.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] A problem X is *hard* for a class of problems C if every problem in C can be reduced to X .
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Thus no problem in C is harder than X , since an algorithm for X allows us to solve any problem in C .
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The notion of hard problems depends on the type of reduction being used.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] For complexity classes larger than P, polynomial-time reductions are commonly used.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] In particular, the set of problems that are hard for NP is the set of NP-hard problems.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] If a problem X is in C and hard for C , then X is said to be *complete* for C .
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] This means that X is the hardest problem in C .
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] (Since many problems could be equally hard, one might say that X is one of the hardest problems in C .) Thus the class of NP-complete problems contains the most difficult problems in NP, in the sense that they are the ones most likely not to be in P.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Because the problem P = NP is not solved, being able to reduce a known NP-complete problem, $\Pi _{2}$ , to another problem, $\Pi _{1}$ , would indicate that there is no known polynomial-time solution for $\Pi _{1}$ .
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] This is because a polynomial-time solution to $\Pi _{1}$ would yield a polynomial-time solution to $\Pi _{2}$ .
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Similarly, because all NP problems can be reduced to the set, finding an NP-complete problem that can be solved in polynomial time would mean that P = NP.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The complexity class P is often seen as a mathematical abstraction modeling those computational tasks that admit an efficient algorithm.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] This hypothesis is called the Cobham–Edmonds thesis.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The complexity class NP, on the other hand, contains many problems that people would like to solve efficiently, but for which no efficient algorithm is known, such as the Boolean satisfiability problem, the Hamiltonian path problem and the vertex cover problem.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Since deterministic Turing machines are special non-deterministic Turing machines, it is easily observed that each problem in P is also a member of the class NP.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The question of whether P equals NP is one of the most important open questions in theoretical computer science because of the wide implications of a solution.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] If the answer is yes, many important problems can be shown to have more efficient solutions.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] These include various types of integer programming problems in operations research, many problems in logistics, protein structure prediction in biology, and the ability to find formal proofs of pure mathematics theorems.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The P versus NP problem is one of the Millennium Prize Problems proposed by the Clay Mathematics Institute.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] There is a US$1,000,000 prize for resolving the problem.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] It was shown by Ladner that if ${\textsf {P}}\neq {\textsf {NP}}$ then there exist problems in ${\textsf {NP}}$ that are neither in ${\textsf {P}}$ nor ${\textsf {NP}}$ -complete.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Such problems are called NP-intermediate problems.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The graph isomorphism problem, the discrete logarithm problem and the integer factorization problem are examples of problems believed to be NP-intermediate.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] They are some of the very few NP problems not known to be in ${\textsf {P}}$ or to be ${\textsf {NP}}$ -complete.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The graph isomorphism problem is the computational problem of determining whether two finite graphs are isomorphic.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] An important unsolved problem in complexity theory is whether the graph isomorphism problem is in ${\textsf {P}}$ , ${\textsf {NP}}$ -complete, or NP-intermediate.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The answer is not known, but it is believed that the problem is at least not NP-complete.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] If graph isomorphism is NP-complete, the polynomial time hierarchy collapses to its second level.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Since it is widely believed that the polynomial hierarchy does not collapse to any finite level, it is believed that graph isomorphism is not NP-complete.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The best algorithm for this problem, due to László Babai and Eugene Luks has run time $O(2^{\sqrt {n\log n}})$ for graphs with n vertices, although some recent work by Babai offers some potentially new perspectives on this.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The integer factorization problem is the computational problem of determining the prime factorization of a given integer.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Phrased as a decision problem, it is the problem of deciding whether the input has a prime factor less than k .
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] No efficient integer factorization algorithm is known, and this fact forms the basis of several modern cryptographic systems, such as the RSA algorithm.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The integer factorization problem is in ${\textsf {NP}}$ and in ${\textsf {co-NP}}$ (and even in UP and co-UP).
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] If the problem is ${\textsf {NP}}$ -complete, the polynomial time hierarchy will collapse to its first level (i.e., ${\textsf {NP}}$ will equal ${\textsf {co-NP}}$ ).
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The best known algorithm for integer factorization is the general number field sieve, which takes time $O(e^{\left({\sqrt[{3}]{\frac {64}{9}}}\right){\sqrt[{3}]{(\log n)}}{\sqrt[{3}]{(\log \log n)^{2}}}})$ to factor an odd integer n .
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] However, the best known quantum algorithm for this problem, Shor's algorithm, does run in polynomial time.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Unfortunately, this fact doesn't say much about where the problem lies with respect to non-quantum complexity classes.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Many known complexity classes are suspected to be unequal, but this has not been proved.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] For instance ${\textsf {P}}\subseteq {\textsf {NP}}\subseteq {\textsf {PP}}\subseteq {\textsf {PSPACE}}$ , but it is possible that ${\textsf {P}}={\textsf {PSPACE}}$ .
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] If ${\textsf {P}}$ is not equal to ${\textsf {NP}}$ , then ${\textsf {P}}$ is not equal to ${\textsf {PSPACE}}$ either.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Since there are many known complexity classes between ${\textsf {P}}$ and ${\textsf {PSPACE}}$ , such as ${\textsf {RP}}$ , ${\textsf {BPP}}$ , ${\textsf {PP}}$ , ${\textsf {BQP}}$ , ${\textsf {MA}}$ , ${\textsf {PH}}$ , etc., it is possible that all these complexity classes collapse to one class.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Proving that any of these classes are unequal would be a major breakthrough in complexity theory.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Along the same lines, ${\textsf {co-NP}}$ is the class containing the complement problems (i.e. problems with the *yes*/*no* answers reversed) of ${\textsf {NP}}$ problems.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] It is believed that ${\textsf {NP}}$ is not equal to ${\textsf {co-NP}}$ ; however, it has not yet been proven.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] It is clear that if these two complexity classes are not equal then ${\textsf {P}}$ is not equal to ${\textsf {NP}}$ , since ${\textsf {P}}={\textsf {co-P}}$ .
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Similarly, it is not known if ${\textsf {L}}$ (the set of all problems that can be solved in logarithmic space) is strictly contained in ${\textsf {P}}$ or equal to ${\textsf {P}}$ .
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Again, there are many complexity classes between the two, such as ${\textsf {NL}}$ and ${\textsf {NC}}$ , and it is not known if they are distinct or equal classes.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] It is suspected that ${\textsf {P}}$ and ${\textsf {BPP}}$ are equal.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] However, it is currently open if ${\textsf {BPP}}={\textsf {NEXP}}$ .
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] A problem that can theoretically be solved, but requires impractically large, near-infinite, amount of resources (e.g., time) to do so, is known as an ***intractable problem***.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Conversely, a problem that can be solved in practice is called a ***tractable problem***, literally "a problem that can be handled".
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The term *infeasible* (literally "cannot be done") is sometimes used interchangeably with *intractable*, though this risks confusion with a feasible solution in mathematical optimization.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Tractable problems are frequently identified with problems that have polynomial-time solutions ( ${\textsf {P}}$ , ${\textsf {PTIME}}$ ); this is known as the Cobham–Edmonds thesis.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Problems that are known to be intractable in this sense include those that are EXPTIME-hard.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] If ${\textsf {NP}}$ is not the same as ${\textsf {P}}$ , then NP-hard problems are also intractable in this sense.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Saying that a problem is not in ${\textsf {P}}$ does not imply that all large cases of the problem are hard or even that most of them are.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] For example, the decision problem in Presburger arithmetic has been shown not to be in ${\textsf {P}}$ , yet algorithms have been written that solve the problem in reasonable times in most cases.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Similarly, algorithms can solve the NP-complete knapsack problem over a wide range of sizes in less than quadratic time and SAT solvers routinely handle large instances of the NP-complete Boolean satisfiability problem.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] To see why exponential-time algorithms are generally unusable in practice, consider a program that makes $2^{n}$ operations before halting.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] For small n , say 100, and assuming for the sake of example that the computer does $10^{12}$ operations each second, the program would run for about $4\times 10^{10}$ years, which is the same order of magnitude as the age of the universe.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Even with a much faster computer, the program would only be useful for very small instances and in that sense the intractability of a problem is somewhat independent of technological progress.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] However, an exponential-time algorithm that takes $1.0001^{n}$ operations is practical until n gets relatively large.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Similarly, a polynomial time algorithm is not always practical.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] If its running time is, say, $n^{15}$ , it is unreasonable to consider it efficient and it is still useless except on small instances.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Indeed, in practice even $n^{3}$ or $n^{2}$ algorithms are often impractical on realistic sizes of problems.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Continuous complexity theory can refer to complexity theory of problems that involve continuous functions that are approximated by discretizations, as studied in numerical analysis.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] One approach to complexity theory of numerical analysis is information based complexity.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Continuous complexity theory can also refer to complexity theory of the use of analog computation, which uses continuous dynamical systems and differential equations.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Control theory can be considered a form of computation and differential equations are used in the modelling of continuous-time and hybrid discrete–continuous-time systems.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] An early example of algorithm complexity analysis is the running time analysis of the Euclidean algorithm done by Gabriel Lamé in 1844.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Before the actual research explicitly devoted to the complexity of algorithmic problems started off, numerous foundations were laid out by various researchers.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Most influential among these was the definition of Turing machines by Alan Turing in 1936, which turned out to be a very robust and flexible simplification of a computer.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The beginning of systematic studies in computational complexity is attributed to the seminal 1965 paper "On the Computational Complexity of Algorithms" by Juris Hartmanis and Richard E.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Stearns, which laid out the definitions of time complexity and space complexity, and proved the hierarchy theorems.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] In addition, in 1965 Edmonds suggested to consider a "good" algorithm to be one with running time bounded by a polynomial of the input size.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Earlier papers studying problems solvable by Turing machines with specific bounded resources include John Myhill's definition of linear bounded automata (Myhill 1960), Raymond Smullyan's study of rudimentary sets (1961), as well as Hisao Yamada's paper on real-time computations (1962).
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] Somewhat earlier, Boris Trakhtenbrot (1956), a pioneer in the field from the USSR, studied another specific complexity measure.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] In 1967, Manuel Blum formulated a set of axioms (now known as Blum axioms) specifying desirable properties of complexity measures on the set of computable functions and proved an important result, the so-called speed-up theorem.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] The field began to flourish in 1971 when Stephen Cook and Leonid Levin proved the existence of practically relevant problems that are NP-complete.
[src:complexity-theory/computational-complexity-theory] In 1972, Richard Karp took this idea a leap forward with his landmark paper, "Reducibility Among Combinatorial Problems", in which he showed that 21 diverse combinatorial and graph theoretical problems, each infamous for its computational intractability, are NP-complete.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] In computational complexity theory, **NP-complete** problems are the hardest of the problems to which *solutions* can be verified *quickly*.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] Each input to the problem is associated with a collection of short (polynomial length) *solutions*, which might or might not validly solve the input.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] The output is "yes" when at least one of these solutions is valid, and "no" when none of them are.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] The validity of each solution can be verified quickly (namely, in polynomial time), and a brute-force search algorithm can find a valid solution (if one exists) by trying all possible solutions.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] The problem can be used to simulate every other problem for which we can verify quickly that a solution is valid.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] Hence, if we could find valid solutions of some NP-complete problem quickly (when they exist), we could quickly find valid solutions for every other problem in which a given solution can be easily verified.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] Problems that meet the first three criteria belong to the class NP, which is short for "nondeterministic polynomial-time".
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] In this name, "nondeterministic" refers to nondeterministic Turing machines, a way of mathematically formalizing the idea of a brute-force search algorithm.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] Polynomial time refers to an amount of time that is considered "quick" for a deterministic algorithm to check a single solution, or for a nondeterministic Turing machine to perform the whole search.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] A problem that is in NP and also meets the fourth criterion is said to be "NP-complete".
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] The term "complete" refers to the property of being able to simulate everything in the same complexity class: If some NP-complete problem has a polynomial time algorithm, all problems in NP do.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] The set of NP-complete problems is often denoted by **NP-C** or **NPC**.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] Although a solution to an NP-complete problem can be *verified* "quickly", there is no known way to *find* a solution quickly.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] That is, the time required to solve the problem using any currently known algorithm increases rapidly as the size of the problem grows.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] As a consequence, determining whether it is possible to solve these problems quickly, called the P versus NP problem, is one of the fundamental unsolved problems in computer science today.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] While a method for computing the solutions to NP-complete problems quickly remains undiscovered, computer scientists and programmers still frequently encounter NP-complete problems.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] NP-complete problems are often addressed by using heuristic methods and approximation algorithms.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] Every problem in NP is reducible to $\scriptstyle C$ in polynomial time.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] $\scriptstyle C$ can be shown to be in NP by demonstrating that a candidate solution to $\scriptstyle C$ can be verified in polynomial time.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] A decision problem that is solvable in polynomial time belongs to the class P.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] All problems in P are necessarily in NP.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] However, it has not been proved that the class NP is actually larger than P.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] In other words, it is not yet known whether there exist problems in NP that are not in P.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] The question of whether the classes P and NP are equal or not is known as the P versus NP problem.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] A consequence of the definition of NP-completeness is that if we had a polynomial time algorithm (on a UTM, or any other Turing-equivalent abstract machine) for $\scriptstyle C$ , we could solve all problems in NP in polynomial time.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] A problem is said to be NP-hard if everything in NP can be transformed in polynomial time into it even though it may not be in NP.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] A problem is NP-complete if it is both in NP and NP-hard.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] The NP-complete problems are thus, in a sense, the hardest problems in NP.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] The Cook–Levin theorem states that the Boolean satisfiability problem is NP-complete, establishing for the first time that such problems do exist.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] In 1972, Richard Karp proved that several other problems were also NP-complete (see Karp's 21 NP-complete problems); thus, there is a class of NP-complete problems, besides Boolean satisfiability.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] Since these original results, thousands of other problems have been shown to be NP-complete by reductions from other problems previously shown to be NP-complete; many of these problems are collected in Garey & Johnson (1979).
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] The easiest way to prove that some new problem is NP-complete is first to prove that it is in NP, and then to reduce some known NP-complete problem to it.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] Therefore, it is useful to know a variety of NP-complete problems.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] The list below contains some well-known problems that are NP-complete when expressed as decision problems.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] To the right is a diagram of some of the problems and the reductions typically used to prove their NP-completeness.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] In this diagram, problems are reduced from bottom to top.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] Note that this diagram is misleading as a description of the mathematical relationship between these problems, as there exists a polynomial-time reduction between any two NP-complete problems; but it indicates where demonstrating this polynomial-time reduction has been easiest.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] There is often only a small difference between a problem in P and an NP-complete problem.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] For example, the 3-satisfiability problem, a restriction of the Boolean satisfiability problem, remains NP-complete, whereas the slightly more restricted 2-satisfiability problem is in P (specifically, it is NL-complete), but the slightly more general max.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] Determining whether a graph can be colored with 2 colors is in P, but with 3 colors is NP-complete, even when restricted to planar graphs.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] Determining if a graph is a cycle or is bipartite is very easy (in L), but finding a maximum bipartite or a maximum cycle subgraph is NP-complete.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] A solution of the knapsack problem within any fixed percentage of the optimal solution can be computed in polynomial time, but finding the optimal solution is NP-complete.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] An interesting example is the graph isomorphism problem, the graph theory problem of determining whether a graph isomorphism exists between two graphs.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] Two graphs are isomorphic if one can be transformed into the other simply by renaming vertices.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] The Subgraph Isomorphism problem is NP-complete.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] The graph isomorphism problem is suspected to be neither in P nor NP-complete, though it is in NP.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] This is an example of a problem that is thought to be *hard*, but is not thought to be NP-complete.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] This class is called NP-Intermediate problems and exists if and only if P≠NP.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] At present, all known algorithms for NP-complete problems require time that is superpolynomial in the input size.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] In the definition of NP-complete given above, the term *reduction* was used in the technical meaning of a polynomial-time many-one reduction.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] Another type of reduction is polynomial-time Turing reduction.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] A problem $\scriptstyle X$ is polynomial-time Turing-reducible to a problem $\scriptstyle Y$ if, given a subroutine that solves $\scriptstyle Y$ in polynomial time, one could write a program that calls this subroutine and solves $\scriptstyle X$ in polynomial time.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] This contrasts with many-one reducibility, which has the restriction that the program can only call the subroutine once, and the return value of the subroutine must be the return value of the program.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] If one defines the analogue to NP-complete with Turing reductions instead of many-one reductions, the resulting set of problems won't be smaller than NP-complete; it is an open question whether it will be any larger.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] Another type of reduction that is also often used to define NP-completeness is the logarithmic-space many-one reduction which is a many-one reduction that can be computed with only a logarithmic amount of space.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] Since every computation that can be done in logarithmic space can also be done in polynomial time it follows that if there is a logarithmic-space many-one reduction then there is also a polynomial-time many-one reduction.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] This type of reduction is more refined than the more usual polynomial-time many-one reductions and it allows us to distinguish more classes such as P-complete.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] Whether under these types of reductions the definition of NP-complete changes is still an open problem.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] All currently known NP-complete problems are NP-complete under log space reductions.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] All currently known NP-complete problems remain NP-complete even under much weaker reductions such as $AC_{0}$ reductions and $NC_{0}$ reductions.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] Some NP-Complete problems such as SAT are known to be complete even under polylogarithmic time projections.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] It is known, however, that AC0 reductions define a strictly smaller class than polynomial-time reductions.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] The concept of NP-completeness was introduced in 1971 (see Cook–Levin theorem), though the term *NP-complete* was introduced later.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] At the 1971 STOC conference, there was a fierce debate between the computer scientists about whether NP-complete problems could be solved in polynomial time on a deterministic Turing machine.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] John Hopcroft brought everyone at the conference to a consensus that the question of whether NP-complete problems are solvable in polynomial time should be put off to be solved at some later date, since nobody had any formal proofs for their claims one way or the other.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] The Clay Mathematics Institute named the P versus NP question one of the seven Millennium Prize Problems in 2000.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] According to Donald Knuth, the name "NP-complete" was popularized by Alfred Aho, John Hopcroft and Jeffrey Ullman in their celebrated textbook "The Design and Analysis of Computer Algorithms".
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] He reports that they introduced the change in the galley proofs for the book (from "polynomially-complete"), in accordance with the results of a poll he had conducted of the theoretical computer science community.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] The following misconceptions are frequent.
[src:complexity-theory/np-completeness] It is not known whether NPC is closed under complementation, since NPC=co-NPC if and only if NP=co-NP, and since NP=co-NP is an open question.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] In computational complexity theory, a computational problem *H* is called **NP-hard** if, for every problem *L* which can be solved in non-deterministic polynomial-time, there is a polynomial-time reduction from *L* to *H*.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] That is, assuming a solution for *H* takes 1 unit time, *H*'s solution can be used to solve *L* in polynomial time.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] As a consequence, finding a polynomial time algorithm to solve a single NP-hard problem would give polynomial time algorithms for all the problems in the complexity class NP.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] As it is suspected, but unproven, that P≠NP, it is unlikely that any polynomial-time algorithms for NP-hard problems exist.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] A simple example of an NP-hard problem is the subset sum problem.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] Informally, if *H* is NP-hard, then it is at least as difficult to solve as the problems in NP.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] However, the opposite direction is not true: some problems are undecidable, and therefore even more difficult to solve than all problems in NP, but they are probably not NP-hard (unless P=NP).
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] A decision problem *H* is NP-hard when for every problem *L* in NP, there is a polynomial-time many-one reduction from *L* to *H*.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] Another definition is to require that there be a polynomial-time reduction from an NP-complete problem *G* to *H*.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] As any problem *L* in NP reduces in polynomial time to *G*, *L* reduces in turn to *H* in polynomial time so this new definition implies the previous one.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] It does not restrict the class NP-hard to decision problems, and it also includes search problems or optimization problems.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] If P ≠ NP, then NP-hard problems could not be solved in polynomial time.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] Some NP-hard optimization problems can be polynomial-time approximated up to some constant approximation ratio (in particular, those in APX) or even up to any approximation ratio (those in PTAS or FPTAS).
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] There are many classes of approximability, each one enabling approximation up to a different level.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] All NP-complete problems are also NP-hard (see List of NP-complete problems).
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] For example, the optimization problem of finding the least-cost cyclic route through all nodes of a weighted graph—commonly known as the travelling salesman problem—is NP-hard.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] The subset sum problem is another example: given a set of integers, does any non-empty subset of them add up to zero?
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] That is a decision problem and happens to be NP-complete.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] There are decision problems that are *NP-hard* but not *NP-complete* such as the halting problem.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] That is the problem which asks "given a program and its input, will it run forever?" That is a *yes*/*no* question and so is a decision problem.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] It is easy to prove that the halting problem is NP-hard but not NP-complete.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] For example, the Boolean satisfiability problem can be reduced to the halting problem by transforming it to the description of a Turing machine that tries all truth value assignments and when it finds one that satisfies the formula it halts and otherwise it goes into an infinite loop.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] It is also easy to see that the halting problem is not in *NP* since all problems in NP are decidable in a finite number of operations, but the halting problem, in general, is undecidable.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] There are also NP-hard problems that are neither *NP-complete* nor *Undecidable*.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] For instance, the language of true quantified Boolean formulas is decidable in polynomial space, but not in non-deterministic polynomial time (unless NP = PSPACE).
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] NP-hard problems do not have to be elements of the complexity class NP.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] Class of problems which are at least as hard as the hardest problems in NP.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] Problems that are NP-hard do not have to be elements of NP; indeed, they may not even be decidable.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] Class of decision problems which contains the hardest problems in NP.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] Each NP-complete problem has to be in NP.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] At most as hard as NP, but not necessarily in NP.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] Decision problems that are both NP-hard and NP-easy, but not necessarily in NP.
[src:complexity-theory/np-hardness] If P and NP are different, then there exist decision problems in the region of NP that fall between P and the NP-complete problems.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] If the solution to a problem can be checked in polynomial time, must the problem be solvable in polynomial time?
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] The **P versus NP problem** is a major unsolved problem in theoretical computer science.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Informally, it asks whether every problem whose solution can be quickly verified can also be quickly solved.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Here, "quickly" means an algorithm exists that solves the task and runs in polynomial time (as opposed to, say, exponential time), meaning the task completion time is bounded above by a polynomial function on the size of the input to the algorithm.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] The general class of questions that some algorithm can answer in polynomial time is "P" or "class P".
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] For some questions, there is no known way to find an answer quickly, but if provided with an answer, it can be verified quickly.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] The class of questions where an answer can be *verified* in polynomial time is "NP", standing for "nondeterministic polynomial time".
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] An answer to the P versus NP question would determine whether problems that can be verified in polynomial time can also be solved in polynomial time.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] If P ≠ NP, which is widely believed, it would mean that there are problems in NP that are harder to compute than to verify: they could not be solved in polynomial time, but the answer could be verified in polynomial time.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] The problem has been called the most important open problem in computer science.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Aside from being an important problem in computational theory, a proof either way would have profound implications for mathematics, cryptography, algorithm research, artificial intelligence, game theory, multimedia processing, philosophy, economics and many other fields.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] It is one of the seven Millennium Prize Problems selected by the Clay Mathematics Institute, each of which carries a US$1,000,000 prize for the first correct solution.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Consider the following yes/no problem: given an incomplete Sudoku grid of size $n^{2}\times n^{2}$ , is there at least one legal solution where every row, column, and $n\times n$ square contains the integers 1 through $n^{2}$ ?
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] It is straightforward to verify "yes" instances of this generalized Sudoku problem given a candidate solution.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] However, it is not known whether there is a polynomial-time algorithm that can correctly answer "yes" or "no" to all instances of this problem.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Therefore, generalized Sudoku is in NP (quickly verifiable), but may or may not be in P (quickly solvable).
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] (It is necessary to consider a generalized version of Sudoku, as any fixed size Sudoku has only a finite number of possible grids.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] The precise statement of the P versus NP problem was introduced in 1971 by Stephen Cook in his seminal paper "The complexity of theorem proving procedures", and independently by Leonid Levin in 1973.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Although the P versus NP problem was formally defined in 1971, there were previous inklings of the underlying problems involved.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] In 1955, mathematician John Nash wrote a letter to the National Security Agency, speculating that the time required to crack a sufficiently complex code would increase exponentially with the length of the key.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] If proved (and Nash was skeptical), this would imply what is now called P ≠ NP, since a proposed key can be verified in polynomial time.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] In a 1956 letter written by Kurt Gödel to John von Neumann, Gödel asked whether theorem-proving (now known to be co-NP-complete) could be solved in quadratic or linear time, and posited that if so, then the discovery of mathematical proofs could be automated.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] The relation between the complexity classes P and NP is studied in computational complexity theory, the part of the theory of computation dealing with the resources required during computation to solve a given problem.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] The most common resources are time (how many steps it takes to solve a problem) and space (how much memory it takes to solve a problem).
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] In such analysis, a model of the computer for which time must be analyzed is required.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Typically such models assume that the computer is *deterministic* (given the computer's present state and any inputs, there is only one possible action that the computer might take) and *sequential* (it performs actions one after the other).
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Since 2001, William Gasarch has conducted three polls of researchers concerning P ≠ NP and related questions.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] The share of responders believing that P ≠ NP was 61% in 2001, 83% in 2011, and 88% in 2018, with 100, 151, and 124 responses, respectively.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] When restricted to experts, 99% of 2018 responders believed P ≠ NP.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] To attack the P = NP question, the concept of NP-completeness is very useful.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] NP-complete problems are problems that any other NP problem is reducible to in polynomial time and whose solution is still verifiable in polynomial time.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] That is, any NP problem can be transformed into any NP-complete problem.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Informally, an NP-complete problem is an NP problem that is at least as "tough" as any other problem in NP.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] NP-hard problems are those at least as hard as NP problems; i.e., all NP problems can be reduced (in polynomial time) to them.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] NP-hard problems need not be in NP; i.e., they need not have solutions verifiable in polynomial time.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] For instance, the Boolean satisfiability problem is NP-complete by the Cook–Levin theorem, so *any* instance of *any* problem in NP can be transformed mechanically into a Boolean satisfiability problem in polynomial time.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] The Boolean satisfiability problem is one of many NP-complete problems.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] If any NP-complete problem is in P, then it would follow that P = NP.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] However, many important problems are NP-complete, and no fast algorithm for any of them is known.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] From the definition alone it is unintuitive that NP-complete problems exist; however, a trivial NP-complete problem can be formulated as follows: given a Turing machine *M* guaranteed to halt in polynomial time, does a polynomial-size input that *M* will accept exist?
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] It is in NP because (given an input) it is simple to check whether *M* accepts the input by simulating *M*; it is NP-complete because the verifier for any particular instance of a problem in NP can be encoded as a polynomial-time machine *M* that takes the solution to be verified as input.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Then the question of whether the instance is a yes or no instance is determined by whether a valid input exists.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] The first natural problem proven to be NP-complete was the Boolean satisfiability problem, also known as SAT.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] As noted above, this is the Cook–Levin theorem; its proof that satisfiability is NP-complete contains technical details about Turing machines as they relate to the definition of NP.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] However, after this problem was proved to be NP-complete, proof by reduction provided a simpler way to show that many other problems are also NP-complete, including the game Sudoku discussed earlier.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] In this case, the proof shows that a solution of Sudoku in polynomial time could also be used to complete Latin squares in polynomial time.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] This in turn gives a solution to the problem of partitioning tri-partite graphs into triangles, which could then be used to find solutions for the special case of SAT known as 3-SAT, which then provides a solution for general Boolean satisfiability.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] So a polynomial-time solution to Sudoku leads, by a series of mechanical transformations, to a polynomial time solution of satisfiability, which in turn can be used to solve any other NP-problem in polynomial time.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Using transformations like this, a vast class of seemingly unrelated problems are all reducible to one another, and are in a sense "the same problem".
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Although it is unknown whether P = NP, problems outside of P are known.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Just as the class P is defined in terms of polynomial running time, the class EXPTIME is the set of all decision problems that have *exponential* running time.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] In other words, any problem in EXPTIME is solvable by a deterministic Turing machine in O(2*p*(*n*)) time, where *p*(*n*) is a polynomial function of *n*.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] A decision problem is EXPTIME-complete if it is in EXPTIME, and every problem in EXPTIME has a polynomial-time many-one reduction to it.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] A number of problems are known to be EXPTIME-complete.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Because it can be shown that P ≠ EXPTIME, these problems are outside P, and so require more than polynomial time.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] In fact, by the time hierarchy theorem, they cannot be solved in significantly less than exponential time.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Examples include finding a perfect strategy for chess positions on an *N* × *N* board and similar problems for other board games.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] The problem of deciding the truth of a statement in Presburger arithmetic requires even more time.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Fischer and Rabin proved in 1974 that every algorithm that decides the truth of Presburger statements of length *n* has a runtime of at least $2^{2^{cn}}$ for some constant *c*.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Hence, the problem is known to need more than exponential run time.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Even more difficult are the undecidable problems, such as the halting problem.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] It is also possible to consider questions other than decision problems.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] One such class, consisting of counting problems, is called #P: whereas an NP problem asks "Are there any solutions?", the corresponding #P problem asks "How many solutions are there?".
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Clearly, a #P problem must be at least as hard as the corresponding NP problem, since a count of solutions immediately tells if at least one solution exists, if the count is greater than zero.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Surprisingly, some #P problems that are believed to be difficult correspond to easy (for example linear-time) P problems.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] For these problems, it is very easy to tell whether solutions exist, but thought to be very hard to tell how many.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Many of these problems are #P-complete, and hence among the hardest problems in #P, since a polynomial time solution to any of them would allow a polynomial time solution to all other #P problems.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Ladner showed that if P ≠ NP, then there exist problems in NP that are neither in P nor NP-complete.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] The graph isomorphism problem, the discrete logarithm problem, and the integer factorization problem are examples of problems believed to be NP-intermediate.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] They are some of the very few NP problems not known to be in P or to be NP-complete.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] An important unsolved problem in complexity theory is whether the graph isomorphism problem is in P, NP-complete, or NP-intermediate.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] The best algorithm for this problem, due to László Babai, runs in quasi-polynomial time.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Phrased as a decision problem, it is the problem of deciding whether the input has a factor less than *k*.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] The integer factorization problem is in NP and in co-NP (and even in UP and co-UP).
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] If the problem is NP-complete, the polynomial time hierarchy will collapse to its first level (i.e., NP = co-NP).
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] The best known quantum algorithm for this problem, Shor's algorithm, runs in polynomial time, although this does not indicate where the problem lies with respect to non-quantum complexity classes.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] All of the above discussion has assumed that P means "easy" and "not in P" means "difficult", an assumption known as *Cobham's thesis*.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] It is a common assumption in complexity theory; but there are caveats.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] A theoretical polynomial algorithm may have extremely large constant factors or exponents, rendering it impractical.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] For example, the problem of deciding whether a graph *G* contains *H* as a minor, where *H* is fixed, can be solved in a running time of *O*(*n*2), where *n* is the number of vertices in *G*.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] However, the big O notation hides a constant that depends superexponentially on *H*.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] The constant is greater than $2\uparrow \uparrow (2\uparrow \uparrow (2\uparrow \uparrow (h/2)))$ (using Knuth's up-arrow notation), and where *h* is the number of vertices in *H*.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] On the other hand, even if a problem is shown to be NP-complete, and even if P ≠ NP, there may still be effective approaches to the problem in practice.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] There are algorithms for many NP-complete problems, such as the knapsack problem, the traveling salesman problem, and the Boolean satisfiability problem, that can solve to optimality many real-world instances in reasonable time.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] The empirical average-case complexity (time vs. problem size) of such algorithms can be surprisingly low.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] An example is the simplex algorithm in linear programming, which works surprisingly well in practice; despite having exponential worst-case time complexity, it runs on par with the best known polynomial-time algorithms.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Finally, there are types of computations which do not conform to the Turing machine model on which P and NP are defined, such as quantum computation and randomized algorithms.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Cook provides a restatement of the problem in *The P Versus NP Problem* as "Does P = NP?" According to polls, most computer scientists believe that P ≠ NP.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] A key reason for this belief is that after decades of studying these problems no one has been able to find a polynomial-time algorithm for any of more than 3,000 important known NP-complete problems (see List of NP-complete problems).
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] These algorithms were sought long before the concept of NP-completeness was even defined (Karp's 21 NP-complete problems, among the first found, were all well-known existing problems at the time they were shown to be NP-complete).
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Furthermore, the result P = NP would imply many other startling results that are currently believed to be false, such as NP = co-NP and P = PH.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] It is also intuitively argued that the existence of problems that are hard to solve but whose solutions are easy to verify matches real-world experience.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] On the other hand, some researchers believe that it is overconfident to believe P ≠ NP and that researchers should also explore proofs of P = NP.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] When one substitutes "linear time on a multitape Turing machine" for "polynomial time" in the definitions of P and NP, one obtains the classes DLIN and NLIN.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] One of the reasons the problem attracts so much attention is the consequences of the possible answers.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Either direction of resolution would advance theory enormously, and perhaps have huge practical consequences as well.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] A proof that P = NP could have stunning practical consequences if the proof leads to efficient methods for solving some of the important problems in NP.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] The potential consequences, both positive and negative, arise since various NP-complete problems are fundamental in many fields.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] It is also very possible that a proof would *not* lead to practical algorithms for NP-complete problems.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] The formulation of the problem does not require that the bounding polynomial be small or even specifically known.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] A non-constructive proof might show a solution exists without specifying either an algorithm to obtain it or a specific bound.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Even if the proof is constructive, showing an explicit bounding polynomial and algorithmic details, if the polynomial is not very low-order the algorithm might not be sufficiently efficient in practice.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] In this case the initial proof would be mainly of interest to theoreticians, but the knowledge that polynomial time solutions are possible would surely spur research into better (and possibly practical) methods to achieve them.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] A solution showing P = NP could upend the field of cryptography, which relies on certain problems being difficult.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] These would need modification or replacement with information-theoretically secure solutions that do not assume P ≠ NP.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] There are also enormous benefits that would follow from rendering tractable many currently mathematically intractable problems.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] For instance, many problems in operations research are NP-complete, such as types of integer programming and the travelling salesman problem.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Efficient solutions to these problems would have enormous implications for logistics.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Many other important problems, such as some problems in protein structure prediction, are also NP-complete; making these problems efficiently solvable could considerably advance life sciences and biotechnology.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] These changes could be insignificant compared to the revolution that efficiently solving NP-complete problems would cause in mathematics itself.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Research mathematicians spend their careers trying to prove theorems, and some proofs have taken decades or even centuries to find after problems have been stated—for instance, Fermat's Last Theorem took over three centuries to prove.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] A method guaranteed to find a proof if a "reasonable" size proof exists, would essentially end this struggle.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] A proof of P ≠ NP would lack the practical computational benefits of a proof that P = NP, but would represent a great advance in computational complexity theory and guide future research.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] It would demonstrate that many common problems cannot be solved efficiently, so that the attention of researchers can be focused on partial solutions or solutions to other problems.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Due to widespread belief in P ≠ NP, much of this focusing of research has already taken place.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] P ≠ NP still leaves open the average-case complexity of hard problems in NP.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] For example, it is possible that SAT requires exponential time in the worst case, but that almost all randomly selected instances of it are efficiently solvable.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Russell Impagliazzo has described five hypothetical "worlds" that could result from different possible resolutions to the average-case complexity question.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] The "world" where P ≠ NP but all problems in NP are tractable in the average case is called "Heuristica" in the paper.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] A Princeton University workshop in 2009 studied the status of the five worlds.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Although the P = NP problem itself remains open despite a million-dollar prize and a huge amount of dedicated research, efforts to solve the problem have led to several new techniques.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] In particular, some of the most fruitful research related to the P = NP problem has been in showing that existing proof techniques are insufficient for answering the question, suggesting novel technical approaches are required.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] These barriers are another reason why NP-complete problems are useful: if a polynomial-time algorithm can be demonstrated for an NP-complete problem, this would solve the P = NP problem in a way not excluded by the above results.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] These barriers lead some computer scientists to suggest the P versus NP problem may be independent of standard axiom systems like ZFC (cannot be proved or disproved within them).
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] An independence result could imply that either P ≠ NP and this is unprovable in (e.g.) ZFC, or that P = NP but it is unprovable in ZFC that any polynomial-time algorithms are correct.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] However, if the problem is undecidable even with much weaker assumptions extending the Peano axioms for integer arithmetic, then nearly polynomial-time algorithms exist for all NP problems.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Therefore, assuming (as most complexity theorists do) some NP problems don't have efficient algorithms, proofs of independence with those techniques are impossible.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] This also implies proving independence from PA or ZFC with current techniques is no easier than proving all NP problems have efficient algorithms.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] The P = NP problem can be restated as certain classes of logical statements, as a result of work in descriptive complexity.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Consider all languages of finite structures with a fixed signature including a linear order relation.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Then, all such languages in P are expressible in first-order logic with the addition of a suitable least fixed-point combinator.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Recursive functions can be defined with this and the order relation.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] As long as the signature contains at least one predicate or function in addition to the distinguished order relation, so that the amount of space taken to store such finite structures is actually polynomial in the number of elements in the structure, this precisely characterizes P.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Similarly, NP is the set of languages expressible in existential second-order logic—that is, second-order logic restricted to exclude universal quantification over relations, functions, and subsets.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] The languages in the polynomial hierarchy, PH, correspond to all of second-order logic.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Thus, the question "is P a proper subset of NP" can be reformulated as "is existential second-order logic able to describe languages (of finite linearly ordered structures with nontrivial signature) that first-order logic with least fixed point cannot?".
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] The word "existential" can even be dropped from the previous characterization, since P = NP if and only if P = PH (as the former would establish that NP = co-NP, which in turn implies that NP = PH).
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] No known algorithm for a NP-complete problem runs in polynomial time.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] However, there are algorithms known for NP-complete problems that if P = NP, the algorithm runs in polynomial time on accepting instances (although with enormous constants, making the algorithm impractical).
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] However, these algorithms do not qualify as polynomial time because their running time on rejecting instances are not polynomial.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] The following algorithm, due to Levin (without any citation), is such an example below.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] It correctly accepts the NP-complete language SUBSET-SUM.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] This is a polynomial-time algorithm accepting an NP-complete language only if P = NP.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] "Accepting" means it gives "yes" answers in polynomial time, but is allowed to run forever when the answer is "no" (also known as a *semi-algorithm*).
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] This algorithm is enormously impractical, even if P = NP.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] If the shortest program that can solve SUBSET-SUM in polynomial time is *b* bits long, the above algorithm will try at least 2*b* − 1 other programs first.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] A *decision problem* is a problem that takes as input some string *w* over an alphabet Σ, and outputs "yes" or "no".
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Formally, P is the set of languages that can be decided by a deterministic polynomial-time Turing machine.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] NP can be defined similarly using nondeterministic Turing machines (the traditional way).
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] However, a modern approach uses the concept of *certificate* and *verifier*.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Formally, NP is the set of languages with a finite alphabet and verifier that runs in polynomial time.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Let *L* be a language over a finite alphabet, Σ.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] 2. the language $L_{R}=\{x\#y:(x,y)\in R\}$ over $\Sigma \cup \{\#\}$ is decidable by a deterministic Turing machine in polynomial time.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] A Turing machine that decides *LR* is called a *verifier* for *L* and a *y* such that (*x*, *y*) ∈ *R* is called a *certificate of membership* of *x* in *L*.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Not all verifiers must be polynomial-time.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] However, for *L* to be in NP, there must be a verifier that runs in polynomial time.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Whether a value of *x* is composite is equivalent to of whether *x* is a member of COMPOSITE.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] It can be shown that COMPOSITE ∈ NP by verifying that it satisfies the above definition (if we identify natural numbers with their binary representations).
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] COMPOSITE also happens to be in P, a fact demonstrated by the invention of the AKS primality test.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] There are many equivalent ways of describing NP-completeness.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Let *L* be a language over a finite alphabet Σ.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] 2. there exists a polynomial-time Turing machine that halts with *f*(*w*) on its tape on any input *w*.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Alternatively, if *L* ∈ NP, and there is another NP-complete problem that can be polynomial-time reduced to *L*, then *L* is NP-complete.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] This is a common way of proving some new problem is NP-complete.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] While the P versus NP problem is generally considered unsolved, many amateur and some professional researchers have claimed solutions.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Woeginger compiled a list of 116 purported proofs from 1986 to 2016, of which 61 were proofs of P = NP, 49 were proofs of P ≠ NP, and 6 proved other results, e.g. that the problem is undecidable.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] Some attempts at resolving P versus NP have received brief media attention, though these attempts have been refuted.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] The film *Travelling Salesman*, by director Timothy Lanzone, is the story of four mathematicians hired by the US government to solve the P versus NP problem.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] In the sixth episode of *The Simpsons*' seventh season "Treehouse of Horror VI", the equation P = NP is seen shortly after Homer accidentally stumbles into the "third dimension".
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] In the second episode of season 2 of *Elementary*, "Solve for X" Holmes and Watson investigate the murders of mathematicians who were attempting to solve P versus NP.
[src:complexity-theory/p-versus-np-problem] In the episode "Put Your Head on My Shoulders" from the second season of the animated series *Futurama*, a visual reference to the P versus NP problem appears in the background.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] A **randomized algorithm** is an algorithm that employs a degree of randomness as part of its logic or procedure.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] In some cases, probabilistic algorithms are the only practical means of solving a problem.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] As a motivating example, consider the problem of finding an ‘*a*’ in an array of *n* elements.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] We give two versions of the algorithm, one Las Vegas algorithm and one Monte Carlo algorithm.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] This algorithm succeeds with probability 1.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Since it is constant, the expected run time over many calls is $\Theta (1)$ .
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] If an ‘*a*’ is found, the algorithm succeeds, else the algorithm fails.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] This algorithm does not guarantee success, but the run time is bounded.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] The number of iterations is always less than or equal to k.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Taking k to be constant the run time (expected and absolute) is $\Theta (1)$ .
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Randomized algorithms are particularly useful when faced with a malicious "adversary" or attacker who deliberately tries to feed a bad input to the algorithm (see worst-case complexity and competitive analysis (online algorithm)) such as in the Prisoner's dilemma.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] It is for this reason that randomness is ubiquitous in cryptography.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] In cryptographic applications, pseudo-random numbers cannot be used, since the adversary can predict them, making the algorithm effectively deterministic.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Therefore, either a source of truly random numbers or a cryptographically secure pseudo-random number generator is required.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Another area in which randomness is inherent is quantum computing.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] In the example above, the Las Vegas algorithm always outputs the correct answer, but its running time is a random variable.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] The Monte Carlo algorithm (related to the Monte Carlo method for simulation) is guaranteed to complete in an amount of time that can be bounded by a function the input size and its parameter *k*, but allows a *small probability of error*.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Observe that any Las Vegas algorithm can be converted into a Monte Carlo algorithm (via Markov's inequality), by having it output an arbitrary, possibly incorrect answer if it fails to complete within a specified time.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Conversely, if an efficient verification procedure exists to check whether an answer is correct, then a Monte Carlo algorithm can be converted into a Las Vegas algorithm by running the Monte Carlo algorithm repeatedly till a correct answer is obtained.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Computational complexity theory models randomized algorithms as *probabilistic Turing machines*.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Both Las Vegas and Monte Carlo algorithms are considered, and several complexity classes are studied.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Problem classes having (possibly nonterminating) algorithms with polynomial time average case running time whose output is always correct are said to be in ZPP.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] The class of problems for which both YES and NO-instances are allowed to be identified with some error is called BPP.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] This class acts as the randomized equivalent of P, i.e.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] BPP represents the class of efficient randomized algorithms.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Quicksort was discovered by Tony Hoare in 1959, and subsequently published in 1961.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] In the same year, Hoare published the quickselect algorithm, which finds the median element of a list in linear expected time.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] It remained open until 1973 whether a deterministic linear-time algorithm existed.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] In 1917, Henry Cabourn Pocklington introduced a randomized algorithm known as Pocklington's algorithm for efficiently finding square roots modulo prime numbers.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] In 1970, Elwyn Berlekamp introduced a randomized algorithm for efficiently computing the roots of a polynomial over a finite field.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Solovay and Volker Strassen discovered a polynomial-time randomized primality test (i.e., determining the primality of a number).
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Rabin demonstrated that the 1976 Miller's primality test could also be turned into a polynomial-time randomized algorithm.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] At that time, no provably polynomial-time deterministic algorithms for primality testing were known.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] One of the earliest randomized data structures is the hash table, which was introduced in 1953 by Hans Peter Luhn at IBM.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Luhn's hash table used chaining to resolve collisions and was also one of the first applications of linked lists.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Subsequently, in 1954, Gene Amdahl, Elaine M.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] McGraw, Nathaniel Rochester, and Arthur Samuel of IBM Research introduced linear probing, although Andrey Ershov independently had the same idea in 1957.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] In 1962, Donald Knuth performed the first correct analysis of linear probing, although the memorandum containing his analysis was not published until much later.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] The first published analysis was due to Konheim and Weiss in 1966.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Early works on hash tables either assumed access to a fully random hash function or assumed that the keys themselves were random.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] In 1979, Carter and Wegman introduced universal hash functions, which they showed could be used to implement chained hash tables with constant expected time per operation.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Early work on randomized data structures also extended beyond hash tables.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] In 1970, Burton Howard Bloom introduced an approximate-membership data structure known as the Bloom filter.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Aragon introduced a randomized balanced search tree known as the treap.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] In the same year, William Pugh introduced another randomized search tree known as the skip list.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Prior to the popularization of randomized algorithms in computer science, Paul Erdős popularized the use of randomized constructions as a mathematical technique for establishing the existence of mathematical objects.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] This technique has become known as the probabilistic method.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Erdős gave his first application of the probabilistic method in 1947, when he used a simple randomized construction to establish the existence of Ramsey graphs.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] He famously used a more sophisticated randomized algorithm in 1959 to establish the existence of graphs with high girth and chromatic number.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Quicksort is a familiar, commonly used algorithm in which randomness can be useful.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Many deterministic versions of this algorithm require *O*(*n*2) time to sort *n* numbers for some well-defined class of degenerate inputs (such as an already sorted array), with the specific class of inputs that generate this behavior defined by the protocol for pivot selection.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] However, if the algorithm selects pivot elements uniformly at random, it has a provably high probability of finishing in *O*(*n* log *n*) time regardless of the characteristics of the input.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] In computational geometry, a standard technique to build a structure like a convex hull or Delaunay triangulation is to randomly permute the input points and then insert them one by one into the existing structure.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] The randomization ensures that the expected number of changes to the structure caused by an insertion is small, and so the expected running time of the algorithm can be bounded from above.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] This technique is known as randomized incremental construction.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Recall that the contraction of two nodes, *u* and *v*, in a (multi-)graph yields a new node *u* ' with edges that are the union of the edges incident on either *u* or *v*, except from any edge(s) connecting *u* and *v*.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Figure 1 gives an example of contraction of vertex *A* and *B*.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] After contraction, the resulting graph may have parallel edges, but contains no self loops.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] In each execution of the outer loop, the algorithm repeats the inner loop until only 2 nodes remain, the corresponding cut is obtained.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] The run time of one execution is $O(n)$ , and *n* denotes the number of vertices.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] After *m* times executions of the outer loop, we output the minimum cut among all the results.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] The figure 2 gives an example of one execution of the algorithm.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] After execution, we get a cut of size 3.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] If *G* is not connected, then *G* can be partitioned into *L* and *R* without any edge between them.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] So the min cut in a disconnected graph is 0.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Initially, *u*,*v* are distinct vertices.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] *As long as we pick an edge ⁠ $f\neq e$ ⁠, u and v do not get merged.* Thus, at the end of the algorithm, we have two compound nodes covering the entire graph, one consisting of the vertices of *L* and the other consisting of the vertices of *R*.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] As in figure 2, the size of min cut is 1, and *C* = {(*A*,*B*)}.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] If we don't select (*A*,*B*) for contraction, we can get the min cut.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Because the min cut is *k*, every vertex *v* must satisfy degree(*v*) ≥ *k*.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Therefore, the sum of the degree is at least *pk*.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] But it is well known that the sum of vertex degrees equals 2|*E*|.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] The probability that the algorithm succeeds is 1 − the probability that all attempts fail.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] By lemma 1, the probability that *C**i* = *C* is the probability that no edge of *C* is selected during iteration *i*.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Consider the inner loop and let *G**j* denote the graph after *j* edge contractions, where *j* ∈ {0, 1, …, *n* − 3}.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] We use the chain rule of conditional possibilities.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] The probability that the edge chosen at iteration *j* is not in *C*, given that no edge of *C* has been chosen before, is $1-{\frac {k}{|E(G_{j})|}}$ .
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Note that *G**j* still has min cut of size *k*, so by Lemma 2, it still has at least ${\frac {(n-j)k}{2}}$ edges.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Thus the probability that the algorithm succeeds is at least $1-\left(1-{\frac {2}{n(n-1)}}\right)^{m}$ .
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] The algorithm finds the min cut with probability $1-{\frac {1}{n}}$ , in time $O(mn)=O(n^{3}\log n)$ .
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Randomness can be viewed as a resource, like space and time.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] Derandomization is then the process of *removing* randomness (or using as little of it as possible).
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] It is not currently known if all algorithms can be derandomized without significantly increasing their running time.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] For instance, in computational complexity, it is unknown whether P = BPP, i.e., we do not know whether we can take an arbitrary randomized algorithm that runs in polynomial time with a small error probability and derandomize it to run in polynomial time without using randomness.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] When the model of computation is restricted to Turing machines, it is currently an open question whether the ability to make random choices allows some problems to be solved in polynomial time that cannot be solved in polynomial time without this ability; this is the question of whether P = BPP.
[src:complexity-theory/randomized-algorithm] However, in other contexts, there are specific examples of problems where randomization yields strict improvements.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] In computability theory and computational complexity theory, a **reduction** is an algorithm for transforming one problem into another problem.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] A sufficiently efficient reduction from one problem to another may be used to show that the second problem is at least as difficult as the first.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] Intuitively, problem *A* is **reducible** to problem *B*, if an algorithm for solving problem *B* efficiently (if it exists) could also be used as a subroutine to solve problem *A* efficiently.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] When this is true, solving *A* cannot be harder than solving *B*.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] "Harder" means having a higher estimate of the required computational resources in a given context (e.g., higher time complexity, greater memory requirement, need for extra hardware processor cores for a parallel solution compared to a single-threaded solution, etc.).
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] The existence of a reduction from *A* to *B* can be written in the shorthand notation *A* ≤m *B*, usually with a subscript on the ≤ to indicate the type of reduction being used (m : many-one reduction, p : polynomial reduction).
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] The mathematical structure generated on a set of problems by the reductions of a particular type generally forms a preorder, whose equivalence classes may be used to define degrees of unsolvability and complexity classes.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] A very simple example of a reduction is from *multiplication* to *squaring*.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] Suppose all we know how to do is to add, subtract, take squares, and divide by two.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] We also have a reduction in the other direction; obviously, if we can multiply two numbers, we can square a number.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] This seems to imply that these two problems are equally hard.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] This kind of reduction corresponds to Turing reduction.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] However, the reduction becomes much harder if we add the restriction that we can only use the squaring function one time, and only at the end.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] Going in the other direction, however, we can certainly square a number with just one multiplication, only at the end.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] Using this limited form of reduction, we have shown the unsurprising result that multiplication is harder in general than squaring.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] Reducibility is a preordering, that is, a reflexive and transitive relation, on **P**(**N**)×**P**(**N**), where **P**(**N**) is the power set of the natural numbers.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] As described in the example above, there are two main types of reductions used in computational complexity theory, the many-one reduction and the Turing reduction.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] Many-one reductions map *instances* of one problem to *instances* of another; Turing reductions *compute* the solution to one problem, assuming the other problem is easy to solve.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] The many-one reduction is a stronger type of Turing reduction, and is more effective at separating problems into distinct complexity classes.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] However, the increased restrictions on many-one reductions make them more difficult to find.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] A problem is complete for a complexity class if every problem in the class reduces to that problem, and it is also in the class itself.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] In this sense the problem represents the class, since any solution to it can, in combination with the reductions, be used to solve every problem in the class.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] However, in order to be useful, reductions must be *easy*.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] However, this does not achieve much, because even though we can solve the new problem, performing the reduction is just as hard as solving the old problem.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] Likewise, a reduction computing a noncomputable function can reduce an undecidable problem to a decidable one.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] Therefore, the appropriate notion of reduction depends on the complexity class being studied.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] When studying the complexity class NP and many harder classes such as the polynomial hierarchy, polynomial-time reductions are used.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] When studying classes within P such as NC and NL, log-space reductions are used.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] Reductions are also used in computability theory to show whether problems are or are not solvable by machines at all; in this case, reductions are restricted only to computable functions (for many-one reductions) or oracle machines (for Turing reductions).
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] In the case of optimization (maximization or minimization) problems, we often think in terms of approximation-preserving reductions.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] Suppose we have two optimization problems such that instances of one problem can be mapped onto instances of the other, in a way that nearly optimal solutions to instances of the latter problem can be transformed back to yield nearly optimal solutions to the former.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] The following example shows how to use reduction from the halting problem to prove that a language is undecidable.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] Suppose *H*(*M*, *w*) is the problem of determining whether a given Turing machine *M* halts (by accepting or rejecting) on input string *w*.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] This language is known to be undecidable.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] Suppose *E*(*M*) is the problem of determining whether the language a given Turing machine *M* accepts is empty (in other words, whether *M* accepts any strings at all).
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] We show that *E* is undecidable by a reduction from *H*.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] To obtain a contradiction, suppose *R* is a decider for *E*.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] We will use this to produce a decider *S* for *H* (which we know does not exist).
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] Given input *M* and *w* (a Turing machine and some input string), define *S*(*M*, *w*) with the following behavior: *S* creates a Turing machine *N* that accepts only if the input string to *N* is *w* and *M* halts on input *w*, and does not halt otherwise.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] The decider *S* can now evaluate *R*(*N*) to check whether the language accepted by *N* is empty.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] If *R* accepts *N*, then the language accepted by *N* is empty, so in particular *M* does not halt on input *w*, so *S* can reject.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] If *R* rejects *N*, then the language accepted by *N* is nonempty, so *M* does halt on input *w*, so *S* can accept.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] Thus, if we had a decider *R* for *E*, we would be able to produce a decider *S* for the halting problem *H*(*M*, *w*) for any machine *M* and input *w*.
[src:complexity-theory/reduction-complexity] Since we know that such an *S* cannot exist, it follows that the language *E* is also undecidable.
[src:complexity-theory/space-complexity] The **space complexity** of an algorithm or a data structure is the amount of memory space required to solve an instance of the computational problem as a function of characteristics of the input.
[src:complexity-theory/space-complexity] It is the memory required by an algorithm until it executes completely.
[src:complexity-theory/space-complexity] This includes the memory space used by its inputs, called **input space**, and any other (auxiliary) memory it uses during execution, which is called **auxiliary space**.
[src:complexity-theory/space-complexity] Similar to time complexity, space complexity is often expressed asymptotically in big *O* notation, such as $O(n),$ $O(n\log n),$ $O(n^{\alpha }),$ $O(2^{n}),$ etc., where n is a characteristic of the input influencing space complexity.
[src:complexity-theory/space-complexity] Analogously to time complexity classes DTIME(f(n)) and NTIME(f(n)), the complexity classes DSPACE(f(n)) and NSPACE(f(n)) are the sets of languages that are decidable by deterministic (respectively, non-deterministic) Turing machines that use $O(f(n))$ space.
[src:complexity-theory/space-complexity] The complexity classes PSPACE and NPSPACE allow f to be any polynomial, analogously to P and NP.
[src:complexity-theory/space-complexity] The space hierarchy theorem states that, for all space-constructible functions $f(n),$ there exists a problem that can be solved by a machine with $f(n)$ memory space, but cannot be solved by a machine with asymptotically less than $f(n)$ space.
[src:complexity-theory/space-complexity] As a direct corollary, ${\mathsf {PSPACE}}={\mathsf {NPSPACE}}.$ This result is surprising because it suggests that non-determinism can reduce the space necessary to solve a problem only by a small amount.
[src:complexity-theory/space-complexity] In contrast, the exponential time hypothesis conjectures that for time complexity, there can be an exponential gap between deterministic and non-deterministic complexity.
[src:complexity-theory/space-complexity] The Immerman–Szelepcsényi theorem states that, again for $f\in \Omega (\log(n)),$ ${\mathsf {NSPACE}}(f(n))$ is closed under complementation.
[src:complexity-theory/space-complexity] This shows another qualitative difference between time and space complexity classes, as nondeterministic time complexity classes are not believed to be closed under complementation; for instance, it is conjectured that NP ≠ co-NP.
[src:complexity-theory/space-complexity] L or LOGSPACE is the set of problems that can be solved by a deterministic Turing machine using only $O(\log n)$ memory space with regards to input size.
[src:complexity-theory/space-complexity] Even a single counter that can index the entire n -bit input requires $\log n$ space, so LOGSPACE algorithms can maintain only a constant number of counters or other variables of similar bit complexity.
[src:complexity-theory/space-complexity] LOGSPACE and other sub-linear space complexity is useful when processing large data that cannot fit into a computer's RAM.
[src:complexity-theory/space-complexity] They are related to Streaming algorithms, but only restrict how much memory can be used, while streaming algorithms have further constraints on how the input is fed into the algorithm.
[src:complexity-theory/space-complexity] This class also sees use in the field of pseudorandomness and derandomization, where researchers consider the open problem of whether L = RL.
[src:complexity-theory/space-complexity] The corresponding nondeterministic space complexity class is NL.
[src:complexity-theory/space-complexity] The term **auxiliary space** refers to space other than that consumed by the input.
[src:complexity-theory/space-complexity] Auxiliary space complexity could be formally defined in terms of a Turing machine with a separate *input tape* which cannot be written to, only read, and a conventional working tape which can be written to.
[src:complexity-theory/space-complexity] The auxiliary space complexity is then defined (and analyzed) via the working tape.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] In theoretical computer science, the **time complexity** is the computational complexity that describes the amount of computer time it takes to run an algorithm.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Time complexity is commonly estimated by counting the number of elementary operations performed by the algorithm, supposing that each elementary operation takes a fixed amount of time to perform.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Thus, the amount of time taken and the number of elementary operations performed by the algorithm are taken to be related by a constant factor.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Since an algorithm's running time may vary among different inputs of the same size, one commonly considers the worst-case time complexity, which is the maximum amount of time required for inputs of a given size.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Less common, and usually specified explicitly, is the average-case complexity, which is the average of the time taken on inputs of a given size (this makes sense because there are only a finite number of possible inputs of a given size).
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] In both cases, the time complexity is generally expressed as a function of the size of the input.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Since this function is generally difficult to compute exactly, and the running time for small inputs is usually not consequential, one commonly focuses on the behavior of the complexity when the input size increases—that is, the asymptotic behavior of the complexity.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Therefore, the time complexity is commonly expressed using big O notation, typically $O(n)$ , $O(n\log n)$ , $O(n^{\alpha })$ , $O(2^{n})$ , etc., where n is the size in units of bits needed to represent the input.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Algorithmic complexities are classified according to the type of function appearing in the big O notation.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] For example, an algorithm with time complexity $O(n)$ is a *linear time algorithm* and an algorithm with time complexity $O(n^{\alpha })$ for some constant $\alpha >0$ is a *polynomial time algorithm*.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] The following table summarizes some classes of commonly encountered time complexities.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] An algorithm is termed **constant time** (often represented as ${\textstyle O(1)}$ time) when its complexity function ${\textstyle T(n)}$ is bounded by a value that does not change with the size of the input.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] This implies that the execution time remains consistent regardless of how much data is processed.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] For instance, accessing a specific element in an array is a constant-time operation, as it requires only a single operation to locate that element.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] In contrast, determining the minimum value in an unordered array is not constant time; it requires examining each element, resulting in linear time complexity, or ${\textstyle O(n)}$ .
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] However, if the number of elements is known and fixed, certain tasks can still be considered constant time.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Importantly, the term "constant time" does not mean the running time must be entirely independent of the problem size; rather, it should have a consistent upper bound irrespective of input size.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] For example, a task that involves swapping the values of a and b to ensure ${\textstyle a\leq b}$ is classified as constant time, even if the execution time may vary depending on whether the condition is already met.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] The key is that there exists a constant t such that the time taken will never exceed t, regardless of the input values.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Constant-time algorithms are especially significant in contexts like cryptography, where timing attacks can exploit variations in execution time.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] By designing algorithms that run in constant time, developers can enhance security and ensure performance predictability, making it a fundamental consideration in software engineering.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to take **logarithmic time** when $T(n)=O(\log n)$ .
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Since $\log _{a}n$ and $\log _{b}n$ are related by a constant multiplier, and such a multiplier is irrelevant to big O classification, the standard usage for logarithmic-time algorithms is $O(\log n)$ regardless of the base of the logarithm appearing in the expression of T.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Algorithms taking logarithmic time are commonly found in operations on binary trees or when using binary search.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] An $O(\log n)$ algorithm is considered highly efficient, as the ratio of the number of operations to the size of the input decreases and tends to zero when n increases.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] An algorithm that must access all elements of its input cannot take logarithmic time, as the time taken for reading an input of size n is of the order of n.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] An example of logarithmic time is given by dictionary search.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Consider a dictionary *D* which contains n entries, sorted in alphabetical order.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] We suppose that, for $1\leq k\leq n$ , one may access the kth entry of the dictionary in a constant time.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Under these hypotheses, the test to see if a word w is in the dictionary may be done in logarithmic time: consider $D\left(\left\lfloor {\frac {n}{2}}\right\rfloor \right)$ , where $\lfloor \;\rfloor$ denotes the floor function.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] If $w=D\left(\left\lfloor {\frac {n}{2}}\right\rfloor \right)$ --that is to say, the word w is exactly in the middle of the dictionary--then we are done.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Otherwise, if it comes after the middle word, continue similarly with the right half of the dictionary.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] This algorithm is similar to the method often used to find an entry in a paper dictionary.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] As a result, the search space within the dictionary decreases as the algorithm gets closer to the target word.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to run in **polylogarithmic time** if its time $T(n)$ is $O{\bigl (}(\log n)^{k}{\bigr )}$ for some constant k.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Another way to write this is $O(\log ^{k}n)$ .
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] For example, matrix chain ordering can be solved in polylogarithmic time on a parallel random-access machine, and a graph can be determined to be planar in a fully dynamic way in $O(\log ^{3}n)$ time per insert/delete operation.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to run in **sub-linear time** (often spelled **sublinear time**) if $T(n)=o(n)$ .
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] In particular this includes algorithms with the time complexities defined above.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] The specific term *sublinear time algorithm* commonly refers to randomized algorithms that sample a small fraction of their inputs and process them efficiently to approximately infer properties of the entire instance.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] This type of sublinear time algorithm is closely related to property testing and statistics.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to take **linear time**, or $O(n)$ time, if its time complexity is $O(n)$ .
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Informally, this means that the running time increases at most linearly with the size of the input.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] More precisely, this means that there is a constant c such that the running time is at most $cn$ for every input of size n.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] For example, a procedure that adds up all elements of a list requires time proportional to the length of the list, if the adding time is constant, or, at least, bounded by a constant.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Linear time is the best possible time complexity in situations where the algorithm has to sequentially read its entire input.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Therefore, much research has been invested into discovering algorithms exhibiting linear time or, at least, nearly linear time.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] This research includes both software and hardware methods.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] There are several hardware technologies which exploit parallelism to provide this.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] An example is content-addressable memory.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] This concept of linear time is used in string matching algorithms such as the Boyer–Moore string-search algorithm and Ukkonen's algorithm.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to run in **quasilinear time** (also referred to as **log-linear time**) if $T(n)=O(n\log ^{k}n)$ for some positive constant k; **linearithmic time** is the case $k=1$ .
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Using soft O notation these algorithms are ${\tilde {O}}(n)$ .
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Quasilinear time algorithms are also $O(n^{1+\varepsilon })$ for every constant $\varepsilon >0$ and thus run faster than any polynomial time algorithm whose time bound includes a term $n^{c}$ for any $c>1$ .
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] In many cases, the $O(n\log n)$ running time is simply the result of performing a $\Theta (\log n)$ operation n times (for the notation, see Big O notation § Family of Bachmann–Landau notations).
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] For example, binary tree sort creates a binary tree by inserting each element of the n-sized array one by one.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Since the insert operation on a self-balancing binary search tree takes $O(\log n)$ time, the entire algorithm takes $O(n\log n)$ time.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Comparison sorts require at least $\Omega (n\log n)$ comparisons in the worst case because $\log(n!)=\Theta (n\log n)$ , by Stirling's approximation.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] They also frequently arise from the recurrence relation ${\textstyle T(n)=2T\left({\frac {n}{2}}\right)+O(n)}$ .
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be **subquadratic time** if $T(n)=o(n^{2})$ .
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] For example, simple, comparison-based sorting algorithms are quadratic (e.g. insertion sort), but more advanced algorithms can be found that are subquadratic (e.g. shell sort).
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] No general-purpose sorts run in linear time, but the change from quadratic to sub-quadratic is of great practical importance.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be of **polynomial time** if its running time is upper bounded by a polynomial expression in the size of the input for the algorithm, that is, *T*(*n*) = *O*(*n**k*) for some positive constant *k*.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Problems for which a deterministic polynomial-time algorithm exists belong to the complexity class **P**, which is central in the field of computational complexity theory.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Cobham's thesis states that polynomial time is a synonym for "tractable", "feasible", "efficient", or "fast".
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] These two concepts are only relevant if the inputs to the algorithms consist of integers.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] The concept of polynomial time leads to several complexity classes in computational complexity theory.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Some important classes defined using polynomial time are the following.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] P is the smallest time-complexity class on a deterministic machine which is robust in terms of machine model changes.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] An algorithm is defined to take **superpolynomial time** if *T*(*n*) is not bounded above by any polynomial; that is, if ⁠ $T(n)\not \in O(n^{c})$ ⁠ for every positive integer *c*.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] For example, an algorithm that runs for 2*n* steps on an input of size *n* requires superpolynomial time (more specifically, exponential time).
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] An algorithm that uses exponential resources is clearly superpolynomial, but some algorithms are only very weakly superpolynomial.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] For example, the Adleman–Pomerance–Rumely primality test runs for *n**O*(log log *n*) time on *n*-bit inputs; this grows faster than any polynomial for large enough *n*, but the input size must become impractically large before it cannot be dominated by a polynomial with small degree.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] An algorithm that requires superpolynomial time lies outside the complexity class **P**.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Cobham's thesis posits that these algorithms are impractical, and in many cases they are.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Since the P versus NP problem is unresolved, it is unknown whether NP-complete problems require superpolynomial time.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] There are some problems for which we know quasi-polynomial time algorithms, but no polynomial time algorithm is known.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Other computational problems with quasi-polynomial time solutions but no known polynomial time solution include the planted clique problem in which the goal is to find a large clique in the union of a clique and a random graph.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] The complexity class **QP** consists of all problems that have quasi-polynomial time algorithms.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] It can be defined in terms of DTIME as follows.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] In complexity theory, the unsolved P versus NP problem asks if all problems in NP have polynomial-time algorithms.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] All the best-known algorithms for NP-complete problems like 3SAT etc. take exponential time.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Indeed, it is conjectured for many natural NP-complete problems that they do not have sub-exponential time algorithms.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Here "sub-exponential time" is taken to mean the second definition presented below.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] (On the other hand, many graph problems represented in the natural way by adjacency matrices are solvable in subexponential time simply because the size of the input is the square of the number of vertices.) This conjecture (for the k-SAT problem) is known as the exponential time hypothesis.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Since it is conjectured that NP-complete problems do not have quasi-polynomial time algorithms, some inapproximability results in the field of approximation algorithms make the assumption that NP-complete problems do not have quasi-polynomial time algorithms.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] For example, see the known inapproximability results for the set cover problem.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] The term **sub-exponential time** is used to express that the running time of some algorithm may grow faster than any polynomial but is still significantly smaller than an exponential.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] In this sense, problems that have sub-exponential time algorithms are somewhat more tractable than those that only have exponential algorithms.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] The precise definition of "sub-exponential" is not generally agreed upon, however the two most widely used are below.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] A problem is said to be sub-exponential time solvable if it can be solved in running times whose logarithms grow smaller than any given polynomial.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] More precisely, a problem is in sub-exponential time if for every *ε* > 0 there exists an algorithm which solves the problem in time *O*(2*n**ε*).
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] The set of all such problems is the complexity class **SUBEXP** which can be defined in terms of DTIME as follows.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] This notion of sub-exponential is non-uniform in terms of *ε* in the sense that *ε* is not part of the input and each ε may have its own algorithm for the problem.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Some authors define sub-exponential time as running times in $2^{o(n)}$ .
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] This definition allows larger running times than the first definition of sub-exponential time.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] An example of such a sub-exponential time algorithm is the best-known classical algorithm for integer factorization, the general number field sieve, which runs in time about $2^{{O}(n^{1/3}(\log n)^{2/3})}$ , where the length of the input is n.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Another example was the graph isomorphism problem, which the best known algorithm from 1982 to 2016 solved in $2^{O\left({\sqrt {n\log n}}\right)}$ .
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] However, at STOC 2016 a quasi-polynomial time algorithm was presented.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] It makes a difference whether the algorithm is allowed to be sub-exponential in the size of the instance, the number of vertices, or the number of edges.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] In parameterized complexity, this difference is made explicit by considering pairs $(L,k)$ of decision problems and parameters *k*.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] More precisely, SUBEPT is the class of all parameterized problems $(L,k)$ for which there is a computable function $f:\mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {N}$ with $f\in o(k)$ and an algorithm that decides *L* in time $2^{f(k)}\cdot {\textsf {poly}}(n)$ .
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] The **exponential time hypothesis** (**ETH**) is that 3SAT, the satisfiability problem of Boolean formulas in conjunctive normal form with at most three literals per clause and with *n* variables, cannot be solved in time 2*o*(*n*).
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] More precisely, the hypothesis is that there is some absolute constant *c* > 0 such that 3SAT cannot be decided in time 2*cn* by any deterministic Turing machine.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] With *m* denoting the number of clauses, ETH is equivalent to the hypothesis that *k*SAT cannot be solved in time 2*o*(*m*) for any integer *k* ≥ 3.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] The exponential time hypothesis implies P ≠ NP.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be **exponential time**, if *T*(*n*) is upper bounded by 2poly(*n*), where poly(*n*) is some polynomial in *n*.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] More formally, an algorithm is exponential time if *T*(*n*) is bounded by *O*(2*n**k*) for some constant *k*.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Problems which admit exponential time algorithms on a deterministic Turing machine form the complexity class known as **EXP**.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Sometimes, exponential time is used to refer to algorithms that have *T*(*n*) = 2*O*(*n*), where the exponent is at most a linear function of *n*.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] This gives rise to the complexity class **E**.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be **factorial time** if *T(n)* is upper bounded by the factorial function *n!*.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Factorial time is a subset of exponential time (EXP) because $n!\leq n^{n}=2^{n\log n}=O\left(2^{n^{1+\epsilon }}\right)$ for all $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] An example of an algorithm that runs in factorial time is bogosort, a notoriously inefficient sorting algorithm based on trial and error.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Bogosort sorts a list of *n* items by repeatedly shuffling the list until it is found to be sorted.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] In the average case, each pass through the bogosort algorithm will examine one of the *n*! orderings of the *n* items.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] If the items are distinct, only one such ordering is sorted.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Bogosort shares patrimony with the infinite monkey theorem.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be double exponential time if *T*(*n*) is upper bounded by 22poly(*n*), where poly(*n*) is some polynomial in *n*.
[src:complexity-theory/time-complexity] Such algorithms belong to the complexity class 2-EXPTIME.
